article.description:
Nicole Powell scored 13 points to lead a 
balanced attack as the Sacramento Monarchs held off the
cold-shooting Phoenix Mercury, 77-72, in the season opener for
both teams.

article.headline: Powell leads balanced Sacramento attack
article.linkText: Monarchs top Mercury for 9th time in 10 meetings
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Nicole Powell scored 13 points in her Sacramento
debut to lead the Monarchs past the Phoenix Mercury 77-72 Saturday
night in the season opener for both teams.

DeMya Walker also had 13 points, Yolanda Griffith had 11 and
Powell added six rebounds and six assists for Sacramento, which
built a 12-point lead in the second half before the Mercury pulled
within three in the final 2 minutes.

Diana Taurasi and Anna DeForge each had 20 points for the
Mercury, but the pair missed 23 of 34 shots. Phoenix missed 10 of
its first 13 attempts from the floor and shot just 30 percent for
the game.

Powell, the third overall pick out of Stanford a year ago, spent
her rookie season in Charlotte. She joined Sacramento during the
offseason in a deal for Tangela Smith.

"I think for our first game on the road we picked up on some
things that we need to work," Powell said. "It wasn't pretty, but
we got it."

She made a pair of free throws with 49 seconds left, then hit
Walker for an easy basket with 18.8 seconds remaining to put
Sacramento ahead 70-65. Ticha Penicheiro added four free throws in
the final 6.7 seconds to seal it.

Sacramento made 16 of 30 shots in the first half to build a
42-33 lead at intermission.

Phoenix began the season without projected starters Penny Taylor
and Kamila Vodichkova. They are expected to be with their overseas
teams through the month of May.

"We shot too early, we didn't execute the offense, so we didn't
give ourselves an opportunity to get great, wide-open looks,"
Mercury coach Carrie Graf said. "I think we turned it around in
the second half, particularly from the free throw line, but we were
a disaster in the first half."
